es\n*[[Anders Frid\u00e9n]] - [[Singing|vocals]], additional [[Percussion instrument|percussion]]\n*[[Jesper Str\u00f6mblad]] - [[lead guitar]], [[Keyboard instrument|keyboards]], additional percussion\n*[[Glenn Ljungstr\u00f6m]] - [[rhythm guitar]]\n*[[Johan Larsson (musician)|Johan Larsson]] - [[bass guitar|bass]]\n*[[Bj\u00f6rn Gelotte]] - [[Drum kit|drums]], percussion & additional lead guitar\n\n;Other personnel\n*Ulrika Netterdahl - female vocals on \"Whoracle\"\n*The ''Whoracle'' concept conjured and verbalized by [[Niklas Sundin]] and Anders Frid\u00e9n.\n*Lyrics written by Niklas Sundin following original synopsis by Anders Frid\u00e9n.\n*All music composed and arranged by In Flames except \"Everything Counts\" by [[Martin Lee Gore]] of [[Depeche Mode]].\n*Recorded and produced by [[Fredrik Nordstr\u00f6m]] with assistance from In Flames.\n*Engineered by Anders Frid\u00e9n and Fredrik Nordstr\u00f6m.\n*Mixed by Fredrik Nordstr\u00f6m and Anders Frid\u00e9n.\n*Mastered by Goran Finnberg and Fredrik Nordstrom at the Mastering Room Gbg.\n*Cover artwork by Andreas Marschall.\n*Photos by [[Kenneth Johansson]].\n*All songs published by Prophecies Publishing Hamburg except \"Everything Counts\".\n*\"Everything Counts\" published by Grabbing Hands Music Ltd, sub-published by [[EMI|EMI Music Germany]].\n\n==References==\n<references/>\n\n{{In Flames}}\n\n[[Category:In Flames albums]]\n[[Category:Nuclear Blast albums]]\n[[Category:1997 albums]]\n[[Category:Concept albums]]\n[[Category:Albums recorded at Studio Fredman]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Fredrik Nordstr\u00f6m]]\n", "name_user": "Urgal", "label": "safe", "comment": "they play other genres as well", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Whoracle"}
{"title_page": "Conway the Machine", "text_new": "{{short description|American rapper}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Conway the Machine\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = Demond Price\n| alias            = {{hlist|Reject|Nash|The Machine}}\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1982|2|16}}\n| birth_place      = [[Buffalo, New York]], U.S.\n| origin           = \n| genre            = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| occupation       = [[Rapping|Rapper]]\n| instrument       = [[Vocals]]\n| years_active     = 2012\u2013present\n| label            = {{hlist|Daupe!|Griselda|[[Shady Records|Shady]]}}\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[The Alchemist (musician)|The Alchemist]]|[[Benny The Butcher]]|Daringer|[[Westside Gunn]]}}\n| website          = \n}}\n\n'''Demond Price''' (born February 16, 1982), known professionally as '''Conway the Machine''' (or simply '''Conway'''), is an American rapper. Conway was born in Buffalo, New York, and is the older cousin of and frequent collaborator with [[Benny The Butcher]] and [[Westside Gunn]].\n\n== History ==\n===2012\u20132019: Early mixtapes and ''G.O.A.T.''===\nAt age 23, Conway spent some time in jail, which he has cited as a motivation for weaning from a gangster lifestyle to focus on his career in music.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/11/artist-of-the-month-conway-on-repping-buffalo-second-chances-and-being-the-grimiest-of-all-time/|title=Artist of the Month Conway on Repping Buffalo, Second Chances, and Being the Grimiest of All Time|date=2017-11-16|website=Consequence of Sound|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012 Conway was shot in the back of the head and neck, an incident that left him with Bell's Palsy, which paralyzed the right half of his face. Much like former Eminem signee [[50 Cent]], Conway proceeded to use this near-death experience in his music, which often depicts hyper-realistic street violence told from a first person perspective. Furthermore, his facial paralysis contributed to what [[Consequence of Sound]] described as \"a mush-mouthed, yet visceral flow reflecting the sheer force of will needed to overcome the incident that could have easily ended his career\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/1919138/prepare-yourself-for-conways-bleak-dusty-evocative-street-rap/franchises/status-aint-hood/|title=Prepare Yourself For Conway\u2019s Bleak, Dusty, Evocative Street-Rap|date=2017-01-11|website=Stereogum|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/conway-goat/|title=Conway: G.O.A.T.|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Westside Gunn founded Griselda Records, through which Conway and Westside Gunn would self-release their own projects and the works of artists such as [[Benny The Butcher]] and Tha God Fahim.  In 2015 Conway released his first two official mixtape projects through Griselda Records, ''The Devil's Reject'' and ''Reject 2''.  Conway and Westside Gunn also released two collaborative EPs through London based record label Daupe!,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/label/489399-Daupe!|title=Daupe!|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref> the first of which was 2015's ''Hall & Nash'', followed by 2016's ''Griselda Ghost''. In April 2016, during [[Mobb Deep]] and [[Smif-N-Wessun]]'s \"Hell On Earth\" tour, Conway was introduced to Prodigy of Mobb Deep, who would become one of his earliest notable collaborators and supporters.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn March 3, 2017, Griselda Records signed a deal with [[Eminem]]'s [[Shady Records]], a subsidiary of [[Interscope Records|Interscope]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://shadyrecords.com/2017/03/03/shady-x-griselda-ink-deal-for-westside-gunn-and-conway/|title=Shady X Griselda Ink Deal For Westside Gunn and Conway|website=Shady Records|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref><ref>https://www.npr.org/transcripts/789690521</ref> On October 10, 2017, Conway contributed an a cappella rap verse to the 2017 [[BET Hip Hop Awards]] Shady cypher.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.xxlmag.com/video/2017/10/conway-boogie-shady-2017-bet-hip-hop-awards-cypher/|title=Conway, Boogie and More Spit in Shady 2017 BET Hip Hop Awards Cypher - XXL|last=Mojica|first=Nick|website=XXL Mag|language=en|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref>  The same year, [[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] included Westside Gunn and Conway in their list of \"15 Best Unofficial Rap Duos in the Game\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2017/07/when-these-rappers-pair-up-something-special-happens/|title=The 15 Best Unofficial Rap Duos in the Game Right Now|website=Complex|language=en|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref> as well as two of the \"17 Artists to Watch in 2017\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2017/01/artists-to-watch-in-2017|title=17 Artists to Watch in 2017|website=Complex|language=en|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref>\n\nFollowing Griselda's deal with Shady Records, Conway's first official release was ''G.O.A.T.'' (Grimiest Of All Time) in December 2017, which included production from Griselda's in-house producer Daringer, and featured verses from [[Royce da 5'9\"]], [[Raekwon]], [[Prodigy (rapper)|Prodigy]], [[Styles P]] and [[Lloyd Banks]].  Earlier in 2017 he released a collaborative mixtape with [[DJ Green Lantern]] titled ''More Steroids''.\n\nMuch like Lil Wayne and 50 Cent before him,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.redbull.com/us-en/top-10-best-lil-wayne-mixtapes|title=10 Best Lil Wayne Mixtapes|website=Red Bull|language=en|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stopthebreaks.com/independent-case-studies/how-50-cent-used-mixtapes-to-market-his-brand/|title=How 50 Cent Used Mixtapes To Market His Brand \u2013 Stop The Breaks {{!}} Independent Music Grind|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref> Conway has made a name releasing frequent and well received mixtapes online, often for free.  His mixtape collaborations for his ''Everybody Is F.O.O.D.'' series has included [[Busta Rhymes]], [[Pete Rock]], [[The Alchemist (musician)|The Alchemist]], [[Nottz]], and [[Statik Selektah]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thesource.com/2018/04/08/conway-the-machine-releases-new-project-blakk-tape/|title=Conway The Machine Releases New Project \"Blakk Tape\"|last=Sanchez|first=The Lesson w/ DJ|date=2018-04-08|website=The Source|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref> He has also made countless collaborations and features with other underground artists and Dj's alike such as NEMS, Pounds, Old Droog, Leaf Dog, DARINGER, Alchemist, DJ Muggs, DJ Premier etc.>\n\n===2019\u2013present: ''God Don't Make Mistakes'' & ''Look What I Became''===\nOn May 16, 2019, Conway, [[Benny The Butcher]] and [[Westside Gunn]] released their first single with [[DJ Premier]] titled \"Headlines\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://djbooth.net/features/2019-05-17-dj-premier-griselda-gang-headlines-interviews|title=DJ Premier & Griselda Interview: Making \"Headlines\"|last=Chesman|first=Donna-Claire|website=DJBooth|language=en|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref>\n\nConway released \"Bang\", the first single off ''God Don't Make Mistakes'', alongside [[Eminem]] on July 19, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2051790/conway-the-machine-bang-feat-eminem/music/|title=Conway The Machine \u2013 \"Bang\" (Feat. Eminem)|date=2019-07-19|website=Stereogum|access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2019/07/conway-the-machine-eminem-bang/|title=Listen to Eminem's Guest Verse on Conway the Machine's \"Bang\"|date=2019-07-19|website=Spin|access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref>During a Djvlad interview released on Aug 21, 2019 he had confirmed [[ScHoolboy Q]], [[Rapsody]], and [[50 Cent]] would be some features on the album and there would be a lead up project before it called \"Look What I Became.\"\n\nOn September 7th, 2019 Conway had officially revealed the release date of the Look What I've Became mixtape on Instagram <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B2B6A8AgS4L/|title=\u201cLook What I Became...\u201dSeptember 13th|date=2019-09-19|website=Instagram|access-date=2019-09-14}}</ref> and it released on September 13th, 2019 with features from Dave East and more.\n\nSpeaking on Conway's 2019 work Dan-O of Freemusicempire said \"Conway went beyond skill this year, into himself, with rewarding results.\" <ref>http://freemusicempire.com/2019/12/24/2019-fme-mvp-griselda</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Collaboration albums ===\n* ''Lulu'' (with [[The Alchemist (record producer)|The Alchemist]]) (2020)\n\n=== Compilation albums ===\n* ''Organized Grime'' {{Small|(released under Trillmatic Goods)}} (2019)\n\n=== Mixtapes ===\n\n* ''The Devil's Reject'' (2015)\n* ''Reject 2'' (2015)\n* ''Reject on Steroids'' (2017)\n* ''G.O.A.T.'' (2017)\n* ''Blakk Tape'' (2018)\n* ''Everybody Is F.O.O.D'' (2018)\n* ''EIF 2: Eat What U Kill'' (2018)\n* ''Everybody Is F.O.O.D 3'' (2019)\n* ''Look What I Became'' (2019)\n\n=== Compilation mixtapes ===\n\n* ''El Patron'' (2016)\n\n* ''50 Round Drum'' (2016)\n\n=== Collaboration mixtapes ===\n\n* ''Hall and Nash'' {{Small|(with Westside Gunn as Hall 'N Nash)}} (2015)\n* ''Griselda Ghost'' {{Small|(with Westside Gunn as Hall 'N Nash)}} (2015)\n* ''[[Hell Still On Earth|Hell Still On Earth EP]]'' {{Small|(with Prodigy)}}  (2016)\n* ''[[Don't Get Scared Now]]'' {{Small|(with Westside Gunn as Hall 'N Nash)}} (2016)\n* ''More Steroids'' {{Small|(with DJ Green Lantern)}} (2017)\n* ''Death By Misadventure'' {{Small|(with Sonnyjim)}} (2018)\n* ''Untitled Drums EP'' {{Small|(with Imported Goods)}} (2018)\n* LuLu {{small | (with [[The Alchemist (musician)|The Alchemist]])}} 2020\n\n=== With Griselda ===\n* ''[[WWCD_(album)|WWCD]]'' (2019)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Conway (Rapper)}}\n[[Category:Five percenters]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Rappers from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:East Coast hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:1982 births]]\n[[Category:Musicians_from_Buffalo,_New_York]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American rapper}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Conway the Machine\n| background       = solo_singer\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = Demond Price\n| alias            = {{hlist|Reject|Nash|The Machine}}\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1982|2|16}}\n| birth_place      = [[Buffalo, New York]], U.S.\n| origin           = \n| genre            = [[Hip hop music|Hip hop]]\n| occupation       = [[Rapping|Rapper]]\n| instrument       = [[Vocals]]\n| years_active     = 2012\u2013present\n| label            = {{hlist|Daupe!|Griselda|[[Shady Records|Shady]]}}\n| associated_acts  = {{hlist|[[The Alchemist (musician)|The Alchemist]]|[[Benny The Butcher]]|Daringer|[[Westside Gunn]]}}\n| website          = \n}}\n\n'''Demond Price''' (born February 16, 1982), known professionally as '''Conway the Machine''' (or simply '''Conway'''), is an American rapper. Conway was born in Buffalo, New York, and is the older cousin of and frequent collaborator with [[Benny The Butcher]] and [[Westside Gunn]].\n\n== History ==\n===2012\u20132019: Early mixtapes and ''G.O.A.T.''===\nAt age 23, Conway spent some time in jail, which he has cited as a motivation for weaning from a gangster lifestyle to focus on his career in music.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://consequenceofsound.net/2017/11/artist-of-the-month-conway-on-repping-buffalo-second-chances-and-being-the-grimiest-of-all-time/|title=Artist of the Month Conway on Repping Buffalo, Second Chances, and Being the Grimiest of All Time|date=2017-11-16|website=Consequence of Sound|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2012 Conway was shot in the back of the head and neck, an incident that left him with Bell's Palsy, which paralyzed the right half of his face. Much like former Eminem signee [[50 Cent]], Conway proceeded to use this near-death experience in his music, which often depicts hyper-realistic street violence told from a first person perspective. Furthermore, his facial paralysis contributed to what [[Consequence of Sound]] described as \"a mush-mouthed, yet visceral flow reflecting the sheer force of will needed to overcome the incident that could have easily ended his career\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/1919138/prepare-yourself-for-conways-bleak-dusty-evocative-street-rap/franchises/status-aint-hood/|title=Prepare Yourself For Conway\u2019s Bleak, Dusty, Evocative Street-Rap|date=2017-01-11|website=Stereogum|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/conway-goat/|title=Conway: G.O.A.T.|website=Pitchfork|language=en|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Westside Gunn founded Griselda Records, through which Conway and Westside Gunn would self-release their own projects and the works of artists such as [[Benny The Butcher]] and Tha God Fahim.  In 2015 Conway released his first two official mixtape projects through Griselda Records, ''The Devil's Reject'' and ''Reject 2''.  Conway and Westside Gunn also released two collaborative EPs through London based record label Daupe!,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.discogs.com/label/489399-Daupe!|title=Daupe!|website=Discogs|language=en|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref> the first of which was 2015's ''Hall & Nash'', followed by 2016's ''Griselda Ghost''. In April 2016, during [[Mobb Deep]] and [[Smif-N-Wessun]]'s \"Hell On Earth\" tour, Conway was introduced to Prodigy of Mobb Deep, who would become one of his earliest notable collaborators and supporters.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn March 3, 2017, Griselda Records signed a deal with [[Eminem]]'s [[Shady Records]], a subsidiary of [[Interscope Records|Interscope]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://shadyrecords.com/2017/03/03/shady-x-griselda-ink-deal-for-westside-gunn-and-conway/|title=Shady X Griselda Ink Deal For Westside Gunn and Conway|website=Shady Records|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref><ref>https://www.npr.org/transcripts/789690521</ref> On October 10, 2017, Conway contributed an a cappella rap verse to the 2017 [[BET Hip Hop Awards]] Shady cypher.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.xxlmag.com/video/2017/10/conway-boogie-shady-2017-bet-hip-hop-awards-cypher/|title=Conway, Boogie and More Spit in Shady 2017 BET Hip Hop Awards Cypher - XXL|last=Mojica|first=Nick|website=XXL Mag|language=en|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref>  The same year, [[Complex (magazine)|Complex]] included Westside Gunn and Conway in their list of \"15 Best Unofficial Rap Duos in the Game\",<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2017/07/when-these-rappers-pair-up-something-special-happens/|title=The 15 Best Unofficial Rap Duos in the Game Right Now|website=Complex|language=en|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref> as well as two of the \"17 Artists to Watch in 2017\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.complex.com/music/2017/01/artists-to-watch-in-2017|title=17 Artists to Watch in 2017|website=Complex|language=en|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref>\n\nFollowing Griselda's deal with Shady Records, Conway's first official release was ''G.O.A.T.'' (Grimiest Of All Time) in December 2017, which included production from Griselda's in-house producer Daringer, and featured verses from [[Royce da 5'9\"]], [[Raekwon]], [[Prodigy (rapper)|Prodigy]], [[Styles P]] and [[Lloyd Banks]].  Earlier in 2017 he released a collaborative mixtape with [[DJ Green Lantern]] titled ''More Steroids''.\n\nMuch like Lil Wayne and 50 Cent before him,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.redbull.com/us-en/top-10-best-lil-wayne-mixtapes|title=10 Best Lil Wayne Mixtapes|website=Red Bull|language=en|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stopthebreaks.com/independent-case-studies/how-50-cent-used-mixtapes-to-market-his-brand/|title=How 50 Cent Used Mixtapes To Market His Brand \u2013 Stop The Breaks {{!}} Independent Music Grind|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref> Conway has made a name releasing frequent and well received mixtapes online, often for free.  His mixtape collaborations for his ''Everybody Is F.O.O.D.'' series has included [[Busta Rhymes]], [[Pete Rock]], [[The Alchemist (musician)|The Alchemist]], [[Nottz]], and [[Statik Selektah]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thesource.com/2018/04/08/conway-the-machine-releases-new-project-blakk-tape/|title=Conway The Machine Releases New Project \"Blakk Tape\"|last=Sanchez|first=The Lesson w/ DJ|date=2018-04-08|website=The Source|language=en-US|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref> He has also made countless collaborations and features with other underground artists and Dj's alike such as NEMS, Pounds, Old Droog, Leaf Dog, DARINGER, Alchemist, DJ Muggs, DJ Premier etc.>\n\n===2019\u2013present: ''God Don't Make Mistakes'' & ''Look What I Became''===\nOn May 16, 2019, Conway, [[Benny The Butcher]] and [[Westside Gunn]] released their first single with [[DJ Premier]] titled \"Headlines\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://djbooth.net/features/2019-05-17-dj-premier-griselda-gang-headlines-interviews|title=DJ Premier & Griselda Interview: Making \"Headlines\"|last=Chesman|first=Donna-Claire|website=DJBooth|language=en|access-date=2019-06-01}}</ref>\n\nConway released \"Bang\", the first single off ''God Don't Make Mistakes'', alongside [[Eminem]] on July 19, 2019.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stereogum.com/2051790/conway-the-machine-bang-feat-eminem/music/|title=Conway The Machine \u2013 \"Bang\" (Feat. Eminem)|date=2019-07-19|website=Stereogum|access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.spin.com/2019/07/conway-the-machine-eminem-bang/|title=Listen to Eminem's Guest Verse on Conway the Machine's \"Bang\"|date=2019-07-19|website=Spin|access-date=2019-07-30}}</ref>During a Djvlad interview released on Aug 21, 2019 he had confirmed [[ScHoolboy Q]], [[Rapsody]], and [[50 Cent]] would be some features on the album and there would be a lead up project before it called \"Look What I Became.\"\n\nOn September 7th, 2019 Conway had officially revealed the release date of the Look What I've Became mixtape on Instagram <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/B2B6A8AgS4L/|title=\u201cLook What I Became...\u201dSeptember 13th|date=2019-09-19|website=Instagram|access-date=2019-09-14}}</ref> and it released on September 13th, 2019 with features from Dave East and more.\n\nSpeaking on Conway's 2019 work Dan-O of Freemusicempire said \"Conway went beyond skill this year, into himself, with rewarding results.\" <ref>http://freemusicempire.com/2019/12/24/2019-fme-mvp-griselda</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n\n=== Collaboration albums ===\n* ''Lulu'' (with [[The Alchemist (record producer)|The Alchemist]]) (2020)\n\n=== Compilation albums ===\n* ''Organized Grime'' {{Small|(released under Trillmatic Goods)}} (2019)\n\n=== Mixtapes ===\n\n* ''The Devil's Reject'' (2015)\n* ''Reject 2'' (2015)\n* ''Reject on Steroids'' (2017)\n* ''G.O.A.T.'' (2017)\n* ''Blakk Tape'' (2018)\n* ''Everybody Is F.O.O.D'' (2018)\n* ''EIF 2: Eat What U Kill'' (2018)\n* ''Everybody Is F.O.O.D 3'' (2019)\n* ''Look What I Became'' (2019)\n\n=== Compilation mixtapes ===\n\n* ''El Patron'' (2016)\n\n* ''50 Round Drum'' (2016)\n\n=== Collaboration mixtapes ===\n\n* ''Hall and Nash'' {{Small|(with Westside Gunn as Hall 'N Nash)}} (2015)\n* ''Griselda Ghost'' {{Small|(with Westside Gunn as Hall 'N Nash)}} (2015)\n* ''[[Hell Still On Earth|Hell Still On Earth EP]]'' {{Small|(with Prodigy)}}  (2016)\n* ''[[Don't Get Scared Now]]'' {{Small|(with Westside Gunn as Hall 'N Nash)}} (2016)\n* ''More Steroids'' {{Small|(with DJ Green Lantern)}} (2017)\n* ''Death By Misadventure'' {{Small|(with Sonnyjim)}} (2018)\n* ''Untitled Drums EP'' {{Small|(with Imported Goods)}} (2018)\n* LuLu {{small | (with [[The Alchemist]])}} 2020\n\n=== With Griselda ===\n* ''[[WWCD_(album)|WWCD]]'' (2019)\n\n==References==\